Q . What is Canonical Constructor?

The canonical constructor in a Java record is the primary constructor that takes one parameter for each
component (field) declared in the record header, in the same order and with the same types. It is
automatically generated by the compiler if you do not provide your own, and it is responsible for
initializing all the record’s fields.

Example

public record Person(String name, int age) { }

The canonical constructor for this record is:

public Person(String name, int age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
}

You can provide your own canonical constructor if you want to add validation or modify the input before
assigning it to the fields:

public record Person(String name, int age) {
    public Person(String name, int age) {
        if (age < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age cannot be negative");
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }
}

Key Points:

(i)   The canonical constructor must have the same parameter list as the record components, in the same
order and types.
(ii)  It is used for object creation and during deserialization if the record is serializable.
(iii) If you don’t define it, the compiler generates it for you automatically[1] [2].